{"/service/ndnp/nmu/batch_nmu_ironweed_ver01/data/sn84020616/00280774224/1908051301/0952.xml":{"full_text":".WFDXTCSn Y. MAT 13,\n1 1 nrAt\"ntiftTni nirtrvW\nPAOT5 FIX.\nEverybody Got Theirs in Good Old \"Met\" Days\nBusi\nan\nE\ntLJS.\nFEATURE\nCROPS ARE MOST\nM\nM\nNCOURAG NG\nYield Promises Large and This\nTends to Create Optimis\ntic Business Outlook.\nNow Tork, May 13. Stocks have\nadvanced from 10 to 30 points since\nthe October panic, and strong efforts\nre being mails to curry them to a\nstill higher level. The query now Is:\nWill these efforts succeed, and If ?o,\non what grounds? Of couise. tin\ngreater portion of this rise was the\nnatural rebound following the panic,\nwhen a'.l securities fi ll far below t )i r\nIntrinsic value owing to compulsory\nliquidation and loss of confidence.\nThe natural level of price to be ex\npected after the panic would depend\nupon a proper readjustment to re\nduce net earnings and to the lower\nrates for niuiii-y winch were liounJ\nto follow the crisis. Wliiie t lie gen\neral depression ef bus'nes wns an nd-'-rse\nluetor to sto. k- t de\ncline in niomy was an ciU.iil buM-i-ii\nf-aetor; and tli. p ay far ma.-tci y\nbetween these trto mrces finally re\nsulted in p.irtical victory .,r the la.\nt. r. This ts the hi-toy nf all panic,\nfince easy mon,y i a i argument for\nthe rise that caniiot be indefinite. y\nresisted.\nIn tile present Instance the advance\nrujM'iiH'iit has been unquestionably\nprolonged by powerful manipulation\nNo important recession, such as\nwould have .broadened the market\nand attracted an outside Interest, has\nyet been permitted. On the contrary,\nprices have been pushed upward with\na persistence that impeded rather\nthan encouraged a real revival of con\nfidence. It was evident that the inur\nket was in control of exceedingly\npowerful operators, whose purposes\nWere not at first very clearly under\nstood. It Is now fully appreciated,\nhowever, that the chief support\ncomes from those Interested In fi\nnancing the requirements of the rail\nroads, and other big corporations dur\ning the current year. The exhaustion\nof the supply if capita; in 197, and\nthe panic which followed, put a stop\nto many of these demands, but, now\nthat money is easier and capital i'\ncoming out of hiding, there is a rush\nto secure co.itrol of ail available sup\nplies. It Is estimated that betw.-i-n\nJ250, 000.000 to J300.000.000 of note,\nbond and stock Issues will have to\nbe taken care of during the remain\ning eight months of l!utj. One cor\nporation alone, the Union Pacific,\nwill shortly finance 140,000, 000 of\nbonds and has secured authority for\nthe issue of another $50,000,000 at\ndiscretion. This authorization, in ad\ndition to others previously granted,\ngives the latter company freedom to\nissue some $258,000,000 new bonds\nand stocks, the uses for which are\nJust now beyond the comprehension\nof the street.\nThe most significant feature of\nIhese numerous issues, however, is\ninn their necessity for that will us\nually be admitted in view of the de\nmand for improved railroad facili\nties but the doubt whether the coun\ntry can raise this amount of new cap\nital at a time when it is suffering\nfrom exceptional business depression.\n.Ml new capital must be provided out\nof the nation's profits from industry\nalone; and, as such profits or savings\nare being severely curtailed, the sup\nply of new capital must be corre\nApondincly limited. Perhaps we can\ndraw somewhat on foreign markets,\nllurope took the Pennsylvania bonds\nnd New York short term notes very\nreadily: but these were prime offer\nlogs, and Bocuritle of a lower grade\nwould, under present conditions,\na very poor market\nliian Say That \"Mol's\" llislrlbutioii of I'liinls Wan '11-I1irtlun.\nkeeping down expenses until business\nrevives.\nTrade reports continue very unsat\nisfactory. acre prices have been\nreadjusted there are some signs of\nrenewed activity; but the holding up\nof prices and wages in many di-purt-tneius\nof industry is simply retarding\nrecovery. The most encouraging\nfeature in any quarter is the crop\noutlook. Thus far the crops hav\nmade an early and satisfactory start;\nmuch better than a year ago. The\nAcreage of cotton promises to be as\nlarge. If not larger, than last year.\nWinter wheat in in fine cond lion, and\nin view of the larger acreage prom\nises a big crop. Should the weather\ncontinue favorable until the harvest\nn June we may even be favored with\na bumper crop of winter wheat.\nNothing will do more toward puding\nthe country out of the \".Slough of De\nspond\" than a good harvest. There\nare prospects of a better export de\nmand for both wheat and cotton,\nwhich, in connection with recent for\neign purchases of securities, will tend\nto retard gold exports, although a re\nsumption of the latter may be antici\npated at no distant date.\nWe repeat our advice of caution in\nstock market operations; for, while\nprices may go higher, there U danger\nof a setback, owing to realizations,\nespecially lu case of a withdrawal of\npresent artificial support.\nMAJOR LEAGUE\nIlatteries; Siever, Schmidt\nPayne; Oieotte and Carrtgan.\nand\nBASEBALL\ns COWS\nHOW Til I IV STAND.\nAmerican League.\nfind\nabroad. These\noperation for the financing of new\n1,-wues are then the chief explanation\nof the prolonged and artificial rise in\nstocks. These new securities must be\ndistributed, and this can only be done\nin a strong market; hence the pow\nerful inside support of the last two\nliionjfbs. The rise has naturally been\ngreatly assisted by easy mor.ey, by\nthe usual rebound after a panic, and\nby the forced covering of demoralized\nand ruined shorts. As for Its con\ntinuance, much depends on the stay\nIme oower of the leaders and their\nholding together. Prices are now\nfully as high as general conditions\nJustify. A moderate business recov\nery ,nd satisfactory election have al\nready been sufficiently discounted for\nthe present, and a partial reaction\nwould be beneficial through broaden\ning the market and bringing In a new\nookiim element which now stands\naloof. On the other hand. It would\nbe foolish to Ignore the power of the\npresent leaders. With an abundance\nof cheap money in their control they\nare likely to carry their advantage to\nthe limit: and. unless unfavorable\nwent Interfere, it need cause no sur\nprise if prices were pushed still\nhigher, or at least held near present\nlevel, until the market leaders have\na.eorni.lished their purpose\nWhether the proposed advance In\nrallro-ad rates is part of the scheme\nto advance the market or not remains\nto be seen, Isuch an advance und\nt xlsling conditions would certainly be\nvery poor policy. The public hostility\nto railroads Is Just beginning to aoat\nthe extreme depression In freight\nwill not last, and the advance would\nbe a burden upon the producer and\nconsumer when be is bast able t\nbear It. No doubt the railroads have\na grievance; but they must do as oth\ners are doing, cut expenses to the lim\nit, endure a temporary shrinkage in\nprofits, and await the resumption of\ntraffic that will surely come In time.\nAny other policy wil certainly revive\npublic hostility and react unfavorably\nupon the railroads themselves. Th\nhad better accept their share of ad\nversity the same as other people, and\ndevote themselves to economy and\ntitate of Ohio, City of Toledo, l.ucas\nCounty, ss:\nKrank J. Cheney makes oath that he\nla senior partner of the tlrm of K. J.\nCheney Co., doing business in the\nCity of Toledo, County and Btaie afore\nsaid, and that said tlrm will pay the\nsum or ONK HUNDKfclU UOl.l.Altn\nror each and every case of Catarrh\nthat cannot be cured by the use ot\nHalls' Catarrh Cure.\nFKANK J. CHUNK.\nSworn to before me and subscribed\nIn my presence, this th day of Decem\nber, A. U.,\nA. W. OL,KASON,\n(Heal.) Notary Public\nHall s Catarrh Cure is taken Internal\nly, and acts directly on the blood and\nmucous surfaces of the sys